{"query": "What are the overall effects of allowing areas of natural or unmanaged vegetation to persist within perennial crops or pastures?", "summary": "Allowing areas of natural or unmanaged vegetation to persist within perennial crops or pastures has multiple documented effects. Natural regeneration of ground cover beneath perennial crops can provide habitat for natural enemies (predatory insects and spiders), with some studies finding more natural enemies in natural ground cover compared to bare ground, though effects vary between different groups of natural enemies (Action 720). Planting flowers or maintaining flowering strips within agricultural areas increases the abundance and species richness of butterflies and moths (Actions 3932, 442), with 23 studies showing that sown wildflower strips had higher species richness and abundance of butterflies compared to conventional field margins or cropped fields. 

For pest regulation, maintaining ground cover in orchards and vineyards can increase natural enemy numbers, with four studies finding more natural enemies in plots with ground cover compared to bare plots (Action 1395). However, effects on pests are mixed - some studies found fewer pests in areas with natural vegetation while others found variable effects depending on pest species (Action 720). Planting flower strips can enhance pest regulation, with three studies showing greater pest reduction or higher proportions of parasitized pests in fields with planted flowers (Action 1400).

Leaving part of crops or pastures unharvested or uncut provides important habitat, with three studies finding increased abundance of predatory insects or spiders, and five studies finding more predators in the unharvested areas themselves (Action 725). Growing native trees within perennial crop plantations can increase butterfly diversity, with one study in Costa Rica finding higher diversity in coffee farms with both native and non-native tree species compared to farms with only non-native trees (Action 3920).", "action_ids": ["720", "242", "3920", "725", "3918", "19", "3932", "442", "1395", "1400"]}

