{"query": "What are the most effective actions for controlling pests in orchards or other perennial tree crops?", "summary": "Based on the evidence reviewed, several actions show effectiveness for controlling pests in orchards and perennial tree crops. Planting or maintaining ground cover in orchards or vineyards (action 1395) has shown mixed but generally positive results, with four studies finding more natural enemies in plots with ground cover compared to bare plots, though effects on pest numbers were inconsistent. Some studies found fewer leafhoppers in cover crop plots, while others found more pests in certain comparisons. Allowing natural regeneration of ground cover beneath perennial crops (action 720) showed varied results, with some studies finding fewer pests and others finding effects varied between different pest groups. Two studies found more natural enemies in natural ground cover compared to bare ground, though effects were sometimes short-term.

Excluding ants that protect pests (action 886) proved effective in several contexts, with studies finding greater parasitism of pests by natural enemies when ants were excluded, and most studies reporting fewer pests when ants were kept out of trees. Isolating colonies of beneficial ants (action 773) also showed positive results, with one study finding lower pest damage to cashews and higher yields when predatory ant colonies were isolated.

Planting flowers (action 1400) to attract beneficial insects showed promise, with three studies finding greater pest reduction or higher proportions of parasitized pests in fields with planted flower strips, and four studies finding more natural enemies in fields with flower strips. Using pesticides only when pests or crop damage reach threshold levels (action 750) generally maintained pest control effectiveness while reducing pesticide applications, with most studies finding similar pest control, crop damage, and yields compared to conventional spraying regimes, along with reduced costs.", "action_ids": ["1395", "720", "886", "773", "1400", "750"]}
